  doi = {10.1111/lam.12385},
  abstract = {Bacteria were isolated from surface disinfected seeds of eight modern\textbackslash ncorn types and an ancestor of corn, teosinte' and identified using 16S\textbackslash nrDNA sequences. From each of the modern corn types we obtained Bacillus\textbackslash nspp. (including, Bacillus amyloliquefaciens and Bacillus subtilis);\textbackslash nwhile from teosinte we obtained only Pantoea agglomerans and\textbackslash nAgrobacterium species. Of these bacteria, only P.agglomerans could\textbackslash nactively grow under hypersaline conditions and increase salt tolerance\textbackslash nof tropical corn seedlings. In laboratory and greenhouse experiments\textbackslash nwhere plants were watered with a 02moll(-1) NaCl solution, P.agglomerans\textbackslash nwas found to enhance the capacity of tropical corn to grow compared to\textbackslash nuninoculated controls. The total dry biomass was significantly higher in\textbackslash nP.agglomerans-treated plants compared to controls under saline water.\textbackslash nGene expression analysis showed the up-regulation of the aquaporin gene\textbackslash nfamily especially plasma membrane integral protein (ZmPIP) genes in\textbackslash nP.agglomerans-treated plants. The plasma membrane integral protein type\textbackslash n2 (PIP2-1) gene in tropical corn seedlings was highly up-regulated by\textbackslash nP.agglomerans treatment under salt stress conditions. Microscopic\textbackslash nexamination of P.agglomerans inoculated seedlings revealed that the\textbackslash nbacterium colonized root meristems densely, and as roots developed, the\textbackslash nbacterium became sparsely located in cell junctions.\textbackslash nSignificance and Impact of the StudyThe enhancement of salt tolerance\textbackslash ncapacity in tropical corn, an important food crop, has the capacity to\textbackslash nincrease its cultivation area and yield in saline soils. The application\textbackslash nof rhizobacteria to improve salt tolerance of tropical corn is\textbackslash necofriendly and cost effective. We show that P.agglomerans isolated from\textbackslash nteosinte (an ancestor of corn) induces salt tolerance in tropical corn\textbackslash nand up-regulation of aquaporin genes. This study shows that microbes\textbackslash nthat increase salt tolerance may be used to enhance crop growth in\textbackslash nsaline soils.},
